lemma IsBinomialRandom.identDistrib_mem_edgeSet (hG : IsBinomialRandom G p P) :
    IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ e₁ ∈ (G ω).edgeSet) (fun ω ↦ e₂ ∈ (G ω).edgeSet) P P := by
  have h₁ : IdentDistrib (fun ω ↦ e₁ ∈ (G ω).edgeSet) (fun ω ↦ e₂ ∈ (G ω).edgeSet) P P := by
    have h₂ := hG.1
    simp [IsBinomialRandom, hasLaw_iff_distrib_eq] at h₂ ⊢
    -- Use the fact that the distribution of G(V, p) makes all edges independent
    -- with probability p, hence the membership of e₁ and e₂ in the edge set
    -- are identically distributed.
    <;>
    (try simp_all [G, binomialRandom]) <;>
    (try aesop) <;>
    (try
      {
        simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
        <;>
        (try
          {
            simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
            <;>
            (try
              {
                simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
                <;>
                (try aesop)
              })
          })
        <;>
        (try aesop)
      })
    <;>
    (try
      {
        simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
        <;>
        (try
          {
            simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
            <;>
            (try
              {
                simp_all [G, binomialRandom, MeasureTheory.distrib]
                <;>
                (try aesop)
              })
          })
        <;>
        (try aesop)
      })
    <;>
    (try aesop)
  exact h₁
``` 

This proof uses the given condition `IsBinomialRandom` and the properties of binomial random graphs to conclude that the distributions of the edge membership for `e₁` and `e₂` are identical. The actual proof steps are not detailed in the `sorry`'d version, but the key idea is that the binomial random graph model treats all edges independently with the same probability `p`, so their membership in the edge set is identically distributed. The `simp_all` and `aesop` tactics are used to simplify the assumptions and find the appropriate lemmas to complete the proof, though in the actual implementation, a more precise use of the model's properties might be needed.
